passages.text: Maintain Rating: BUY | PO: 72.00 USD | Price: 47.26 US

DevSecOps platform vendor GitLab (GTLB) will report F2Q26 results on Wednesday 9/3. Three points into results: (1) proving the GitLab value prop beyond code- generation; (2) progress on Agent Platform; and (3) the potential for a bigger revenue beat. We believe concern that GTLB is at risk from Al is overstated and should be disproven with a steady string of strong results over time. With GTLB shares trading in line with the infrastructure software peer average (i.e., 6.0x EV/CY26E revenue), but forecasted to grow much faster (21% y/y vs. 13% peers), we see compelling risk- reward. Maintain Buy, \(\) 72\(PO.

Our recent rounds of checks suggest that GitLab's leadership position as a DevSecOps efficiency gaining platform continues to be viewed favorably. We believe this should drive healthy adoption of its core offering and its newer Al solutions. While there is still a heavy debate if code- generation tools are credible disruptors to GitLab's value proposition, one thing is certain - Al is generating a lot more code and understanding context and purpose is becoming a lot harder to do. This is where GitLab helps.

We believe the key growth initiative for GitLab over the next 12- 24 months is its Agent Platform, which should become generally available by year- end (currently in public beta). If management commentary on the progress of Agent Platform and initial test customer feedback is positive, we believe this could help build higher confidence that it has the right strategy in place to monetize the future Al DevSecOps opportunity. On the call, we will look to learn as much as possible on what is going on with Agent Platform.

There was disappointment last quarter on the magnitude of the revenue beat, which was the smallest since the company went public (+0.5% vs +2.9% prior four- quarter average). Management did provide an explanation (higher SaaS (software as a service) mix, backend deal linearity), but a strong F2Q revenue beat could better muzzle the bear narrative that it's seeing demand headwinds. We/Street are modeling F2Q26 total revenue of \(\) 226.8m\(/\) \ \(227.4m\) versus guidance of \(\) 226- 227m\(. A 2\%\) revenue beat versus the Street would imply\) \ \(231.9m\) , or \(+27.0\%\) y/y growth compared to \(+26.8\%\) last quarter.

GitLab is a developer of an end-to-end DevOps platform that enables developers to create, review, and deploy code. Key features include: source code management, code review, CI/CD and security. By having a complete end-to-end platform, users should have better transparency, consistency and traceability, versus a basket of best- of- breed DevOps tools.

We believe that GitLab is a potential future DevSecOps share gainer. The company enables organizations the ability to develop and deploy applications efficiently and at scale, which is essential for successful digital transformations and the digital economy of the future. The DevOps ecosystem is currently fragmented, but GitLab's core SCM applications positions the business to become a future platform winner, driving the business to become larger and more profitable over time.

Data from usaspending.gov, the government's official open data source of federal spending information, suggests that GitLab Federal segment revenue could be soft for F2Q26, which could limit revenue upside potential. If the Federal sector is indeed soft, we believe it will likely be caused by lingering disruptions from DOG, rather than anything specific on GitLab's value proposition.

While the F2Q26 Federal data is somewhat concerning, the F3Q26 data is off to a record start with August month data up 170%y/y. We believe this strong data could be driven by locked up budget in F2Q26 being released. Based on monthly data trends, May was the weakest with improvement each month since. Even if F2Q2 proves to be a soft Federal quarter, we believe F3Q26 could be strong.

On Monday 8/25, GitLab announced the appointment of a new Chief Information Officer (CIO), Manu Narayan. Prior to joining GitLab, Narayan served as VP of Business Technology at Confluent, where he helped drive the consumption transformation, along with AI initiatives, and systems and processes. Prior to Confluent, he served on technology teams at BlackLine, Applied Minds, and the CIM Group. Given his consumption model experience, he could help accelerate the Agent Platform strategy. While he is still very new, we could learn more about some of his initial initiatives on next week's earnings call.

Our \(\) 72\(PO is based on an EV/revenue multiple of 10x to our FY27E (C26E) revenue estimate. The multiple implies an EV/revenue/growth multiple of 0.5x, vs. infrastructure peers at 6.0x/0.5x. We believe the premium multiple to peers is warranted given its faster growth, NRR in the 120s, and revenue and free cash flow upside potential, balanced against potential increasing competition from other AI code generation alternatives.
Risks to our PO: 1) valuation risk, 2) competition, 3) deteriorating NRR, 4) extended timeline to profitability, 5) execution, and 6) enterprise software spend can be cyclical.
